WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.060 --> 00:00:06.630
FEMALE SPEAKER: Welcome and
thank you so much for being

00:00:06.630 --> 00:00:08.119
with us here at Google.

00:00:08.119 --> 00:00:08.970
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS: Thanks
for having us.

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:09.500
FEMALE SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:13.005
Now, Brett you have a couple of
frag films to actually show

00:00:13.005 --> 00:00:14.360
us before we started
the interview.

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:16.260
And I believe we're starting
with frag 10.

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:18.500
Tell us a little bit
about this frag.

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:21.340
BRETT LEONARD: Well, what a
frag film is, we have this

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:24.540
idea called PopFictionLife,
which is a way of making

00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:26.380
musical movies that can be

00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:29.390
distributed through the internet.

00:00:29.390 --> 00:00:30.250
But there's still cinema.

00:00:30.250 --> 00:00:31.310
They're not webisodes.

00:00:31.310 --> 00:00:33.200
They're not episodic
in that sense.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:34.910
It's still independent cinema.

00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:36.790
So it's really a feature film.

00:00:36.790 --> 00:00:39.600
But when you're doing
independent cinema these days,

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:44.780
and you don't have Tom Cruise or
giant movie stars in them--

00:00:44.780 --> 00:00:48.680
not to say that you guys aren't
giant movie stars.

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:50.310
You're music stars.

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:55.210
But you have to seduce the
audience to get them to get

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:55.650
into the thing.

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:59.330
So we create what I call
frags, or fragments.

00:00:59.330 --> 00:01:03.840
And we give away half the
movie with fragments--

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:05.319
with these frags.

00:01:05.319 --> 00:01:06.570
You don't get all the story.

00:01:06.570 --> 00:01:07.940
You don't get all the music.

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:11.860
So if you like it, and you want
to see the whole film,

00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:14.650
actually this Sunday, December
9, we've been releasing the

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:16.440
frags over the past
several months.

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:19.610
We're going to be releasing
the entire film for $5

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:23.340
following the example of Louis
CK, who did, I think, an

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:27.590
amazing thing of getting direct
to the consumer with a

00:01:27.590 --> 00:01:31.320
price point that makes sense
for independent content.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:33.480
And if you just want to
watch half of it for

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:34.560
free, that's fine.

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:38.610
Because it's really about not
forcing it down people's

00:01:38.610 --> 00:01:41.100
throats, not doing the
vertically integrated

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:45.390
corporate marketing that
works with mega-movies.

00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:48.400
And what this allows, is it
allows you to do something

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:51.510
that is a little more
creatively free.

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:54.770
Every film in Hollywood now
has to have someone with a

00:01:54.770 --> 00:01:57.780
cape or a cowl or something
like that.

00:01:57.780 --> 00:01:58.320
FEMALE SPEAKER: Nothing
wrong with that.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:01:59.260
BRETT LEONARD: And there's
nothing wrong with that.

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:01.890
I go see those with my son, and
I absolutely love them.

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:02.540
But that's about--

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:04.517
THEODORE PAGANO: We tried
to get capes but he

00:02:04.517 --> 00:02:05.340
wouldn't have it.

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:06.550
FEMALE SPEAKER: I can have
a cape so we're good.

00:02:06.550 --> 00:02:08.139
BRETT LEONARD: So I
always wanted to--

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:10.900
in the past, I've done science
fiction thriller films--

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:15.820
but I love music, and I
wanted to make a rock

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:17.180
and roll road picture.

00:02:17.180 --> 00:02:20.800
And so when it came to that, I
was looking around for a band

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:27.650
and I heard they're called
Burlap to Cashmere and there's

00:02:27.650 --> 00:02:28.950
a song on it called
The Other County.

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:32.880
And I just instantly saw this
movie in my head when I was

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:33.500
listening to it.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:38.840
Then I met the guys and being
characters as they are and

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:42.390
tremendous live musicians, I
thought we had a chance to do

00:02:42.390 --> 00:02:44.550
something where we could
actually record all the music

00:02:44.550 --> 00:02:45.710
when we were doing
the film live.

00:02:45.710 --> 00:02:47.380
So there's no overdubbing.

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:50.990
There's no post-syncing done
here at all in the film.

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:53.210
And they could play essentially
versions of

00:02:53.210 --> 00:02:54.440
themselves.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:58.510
And so when you see this first
frag, Frag 10, which is

00:02:58.510 --> 00:03:02.370
literally being released today
for the first time--

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:04.080
we've been releasing them every
Thursday over the past

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.620
several months--

00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:10.410
they're doing a scene that has
dramatic import to it.

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:11.890
And there's some
truth in there.

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:12.960
There's some fiction in there.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:14.470
But you're not quite sure
which one it is.

00:03:14.470 --> 00:03:18.420
It actually goes back to the
style of Italian neo-realism

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:19.945
more, the films of
John Cassavetes.

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:24.544
Why don't we just watch Frag 10,
and then we can talk about

00:03:24.544 --> 00:03:24.839
