00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:14.900
FEMALE SPEAKER: So tell us what
Frag 10 is all about?

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:16.820
BRETT LEONARD: It's a totally
fictional story about a

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:18.950
fictional manager
named Marcus.

00:08:18.950 --> 00:08:19.590
And--

00:08:19.590 --> 00:08:22.110
FEMALE SPEAKER: A weaselly
guy, isn't he?

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:26.000
BRETT LEONARD: And yet, in every
band, there's always

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:27.910
tensions and things
that happen.

00:08:27.910 --> 00:08:30.390
There are little glimpses of
the truth in there but

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:33.020
obviously hyped and
fictionalized so that the

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:34.110
drama works.

00:08:34.110 --> 00:08:36.990
And it allowed the guys
to pull from their own

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:41.429
experiences, which is in the
genre of neo-realism that's

00:08:41.429 --> 00:08:44.049
something that you try to do.

00:08:44.049 --> 00:08:46.540
And it's a really fun thing,
because you get an

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:50.920
authenticity that is there and
yet you're still playing with

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:53.370
a fictional story so you
can make it go where

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:54.250
you want it to go.

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:58.160
And one of the other things
with the whole genre of

00:08:58.160 --> 00:08:59.650
PopFictionLife is we're

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:02.370
integrating music as narrative.

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:06.950
It really is taking the idea of
what music video has been

00:09:06.950 --> 00:09:10.570
and become and blending it
into narrative even more

00:09:10.570 --> 00:09:11.920
organically.

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:15.650
And I just love music as the
inspiration for cinema,

00:09:15.650 --> 00:09:18.710
because really for me, the
most pure cinema is just

00:09:18.710 --> 00:09:20.820
picture and music.

00:09:20.820 --> 00:09:24.880
And so this is sort of like a
dream come true for me to

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:27.720
create something that
had a musical story.

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:31.430
And the emotions, you don't have
to necessarily have a lot

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:33.020
of dramatic scenes to
convey the emotions

00:09:33.020 --> 00:09:33.970
because the music does.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:36.380
And of course these guys are
such great musicians and are

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:40.700
able to play their instruments
live and do it real that it

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:41.810
give it that authenticity.

00:09:41.810 --> 00:09:44.850
I think that in internet content
in general, people are

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:45.625
looking for authenticity.

00:09:45.625 --> 00:09:48.970
They're looking for something
that's more real, as opposed

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:51.690
to what you should get from
traditional Hollywood

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:52.530
entertainment.

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:55.450
FEMALE SPEAKER: Is that when you
chose to work with music

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:57.330
in particular for these
frag films?

00:09:57.330 --> 00:09:58.500
BRETT LEONARD: Yeah.

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:03.080
It goes back also to the films
of Hal Ashby of the '70s.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:06.460
If you think of Harold and
Maude, that was basically a

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:09.050
Cat Stevens album
put to a story.

00:10:09.050 --> 00:10:12.550
Now would you think that Cat
Stevens would be able to carry

00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:16.650
a story about a suicidal
teenager who has a love affair

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:18.080
with an 83-year-old woman?

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:21.720
Meaning, music and narrative
and cinema can do anything.

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:24.540
They can create any combination
of things and

00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:25.810
actually work.

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:30.210
And so it allows me that
freedom as a filmmaker.

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:32.420
