00:19:24.860 --> 00:19:26.930
FEMALE SPEAKER: I want to talk
a little bit about what

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:30.060
PopFictionLife is and how
the frag film fits

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:31.370
into that new brand.

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:34.500
And then we'll get back to the
band and music itself.

00:19:34.500 --> 00:19:36.700
Tell us what PopFictionLife
is and what

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:38.470
it offers the consumer.

00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:41.920
BRETT LEONARD: It's really
a way of creating and

00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:49.870
distributing independent cinema
in a way that realizes

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:55.330
the reality of getting direct to
consumer, not going through

00:19:55.330 --> 00:19:56.590
the distribution apparatus.

00:19:56.590 --> 00:19:59.140
I mean, I worked in Hollywood
for over 25 years as a

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:00.620
director and producer.

00:20:00.620 --> 00:20:03.260
And the business models of
Hollywood have changed

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:05.530
significantly in that time.

00:20:05.530 --> 00:20:09.360
And primarily, especially for
most independent cinema, it's

00:20:09.360 --> 00:20:12.540
very, very dysfunctional.

00:20:12.540 --> 00:20:17.860
You have a very narrow sort of
window through which most

00:20:17.860 --> 00:20:20.190
things get distributed and
how they distributed.

00:20:20.190 --> 00:20:22.800
And there really is no reason
for that now that we're all

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:24.420
connected in the way we are.

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:26.630
So for people that want to
find different kinds of

00:20:26.630 --> 00:20:29.210
content, it can still be very
high quality content.

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:32.930
It doesn't always have to just
be cats falling out of trees.

00:20:32.930 --> 00:20:37.070
And I think we're leaving that
era of internet content and

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:38.970
moving into much higher
quality content.

00:20:38.970 --> 00:20:41.720
Across the board, there's a lot
of people doing that now.

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:45.210
But PopFictionLife is
specifically designed to also

00:20:45.210 --> 00:20:50.410
allow the idea of frags or being
able to absorb content

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:54.110
through fragments, because it
started for me watching my

00:20:54.110 --> 00:20:57.820
young son and how he looked
at films and content.

00:20:57.820 --> 00:20:59.250
It's an ADD generation--

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:01.740
there's an ADD aspect to
our culture going on.

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:03.920
And people sometimes
will go just watch

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:05.740
one scene of a movie.

00:21:05.740 --> 00:21:07.140
Now, that's not me.

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:09.722
I like to go watch the four hour
version of Lawrence of

00:21:09.722 --> 00:21:13.230
Arabia once a year, because
I just love that kind of

00:21:13.230 --> 00:21:13.880
cinematic experience.

00:21:13.880 --> 00:21:17.060
But that's not really where the
entire culture is going.

00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:22.280
And so in recognizing that,
fragmenting story.

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:24.400
You could even watch these
frags out of order.

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:25.240
You can watch them in any way.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:27.110
You could watch one or two, and
then get excited about the

00:21:27.110 --> 00:21:28.830
story, then go get
the whole film.

00:21:28.830 --> 00:21:33.060
So we're trying to giving the
digital content consumer a

00:21:33.060 --> 00:21:38.680
greater choice in how
they absorb content.

00:21:38.680 --> 00:21:40.730
And also, one of the biggest
things we're going to be

00:21:40.730 --> 00:21:43.990
doing, my partner Christopher
[? Creber ?]

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:47.160
is heading up the interactive
side of PopFictionLife.

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:51.570
And frags are designed to
create interactivity.

00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:53.200
If you look at some of the stuff
that's happened here

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:57.780
Google with Chris Milk and what
he did with Arcade Fire.

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:00.250
Frags are designed to have
interactivity with them and

00:22:00.250 --> 00:22:03.670
yet still maintain the integrity
of being a full

00:22:03.670 --> 00:22:05.010
independent feature film.

00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:05.750
FEMALE SPEAKER: How
does that work?

00:22:05.750 --> 00:22:09.290
How does the interactivity
between the users work?

00:22:09.290 --> 00:22:10.790
BRETT LEONARD: Well that's
a big question, isn't it?

00:22:10.790 --> 00:22:12.910
That's what everyone's trying
to figure out these days.

00:22:12.910 --> 00:22:15.980
I think one, obviously
integration into social media,

00:22:15.980 --> 00:22:18.490
which we're doing a lot
of is very important.

00:22:18.490 --> 00:22:20.950
So that people can discuss
and talk about things.

00:22:20.950 --> 00:22:24.610
It's also about showing how this
kind of content can be

00:22:24.610 --> 00:22:27.410
made, because it can be made
very, very, very cost

00:22:27.410 --> 00:22:29.680
effectively and yet
at a high quality.

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:33.780
And all the tools are coming
down to really a generation

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.280
that I believe is going to
be communicating through

00:22:36.280 --> 00:22:38.470
cinematic language
much more than

00:22:38.470 --> 00:22:40.070
almost any other language.

00:22:40.070 --> 00:22:43.960
And in a sense, cinematic
language is a global language.

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:48.250
And so by doing these kinds of
projects, using the expertise

00:22:48.250 --> 00:22:50.700
of Hollywood filmmaking, but
sort of doing it in the same

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:53.350
way that a lot of very young
filmmakers out there.

00:22:53.350 --> 00:22:56.450
I basically mentor and employ
a lot of young filmmakers to

00:22:56.450 --> 00:22:58.120
make these films.

00:22:58.120 --> 00:23:01.340
Because the way they are
integrating with the tools,

00:23:01.340 --> 00:23:03.710
the way they think about
cinema, is completely

00:23:03.710 --> 00:23:05.860
different than my generation.

00:23:05.860 --> 00:23:10.040
And it's very exciting to me,
because I think it's about the

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:12.470
march of cinematic language
moving forward and becoming

00:23:12.470 --> 00:23:14.850
truly interactive.

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:17.930
Gaming is obviously becoming
more and more cinematic and

00:23:17.930 --> 00:23:18.910
yet is very interactive.

00:23:18.910 --> 00:23:22.330
I think there's so many more
places to go with that that

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:24.940
aren't just in these narrow
areas that are

00:23:24.940 --> 00:23:26.140
happening right now.

00:23:26.140 --> 00:23:28.870
And you can do interactivity
with emotions.

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:30.640
You can do interactivity
with the way in

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:32.310
which you create something.

00:23:32.310 --> 00:23:35.610
That alone and integrating with
a community of people

00:23:35.610 --> 00:23:40.630
that are making content with
tools that allow them to make

00:23:40.630 --> 00:23:43.220
it compelling.

00:23:43.220 --> 00:23:44.890
Because it is a language.

00:23:44.890 --> 00:23:47.420
It's not just an art
form at this point.

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:54.170
Every language started as an
art form and then became

00:23:54.170 --> 00:23:56.890
something more consistent
as a language over time.

00:23:56.890 --> 00:23:58.440
If you look at the printing
press, if you look at

00:23:58.440 --> 00:24:01.200
calligraphy, all the things that
have developed over the

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:04.630
ages, and so I think cinema
is that global language.

00:24:04.630 --> 00:24:08.710
And I happen to believe that
cinematic language has a great

00:24:08.710 --> 00:24:09.980
hope to it, because it

00:24:09.980 --> 00:24:11.800
translates across all barriers.

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:16.340
And so if you can teach people
how to create compelling

00:24:16.340 --> 00:24:20.680
cinematic language and also get
it out there in a way that

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:24.350
can truly find its audience,
there's great things that can

00:24:24.350 --> 00:24:24.740
happen there.

00:24:24.740 --> 00:24:31.340
We've obviously seen certain
things like, Facebook movies

00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:34.430
and things that are showing that
this is something that's

00:24:34.430 --> 00:24:37.230
really developing in the
global mind frame.

00:24:37.230 --> 00:24:38.730
And it's an exciting time.

00:24:38.730 --> 00:24:40.230
So this is a reaction.

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:43.270
PopFictionLife is a reaction
to all that.

