00:27:33.570 --> 00:27:34.960
content creators that
are out of there

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:35.780
that are also consumers.

00:27:35.780 --> 00:27:39.190
So this is all stuff that we're
developing right now.

00:27:39.190 --> 00:27:42.880
We wanted to start by making a
frag film that was compelling

00:27:42.880 --> 00:27:45.176
and for a broad audience,
and that's what The

00:27:45.176 --> 00:27:46.410
Other Country is.

00:27:46.410 --> 00:27:48.850
FEMALE SPEAKER: So now, you guys
as a band have a really

00:27:48.850 --> 00:27:49.720
interesting story.

00:27:49.720 --> 00:27:52.790
You had a successful debut album
and then you disappeared

00:27:52.790 --> 00:27:53.550
for 10 years.

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:56.220
And now you're back with
a self-titled album.

00:27:56.220 --> 00:27:58.240
What encouraged you
guys to come back

00:27:58.240 --> 00:27:59.100
and get back together?

00:27:59.100 --> 00:28:01.280
And what were you able to bring
to this record after a

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:05.590
10 year hiatus?

00:28:05.590 --> 00:28:06.230
THEODORE PAGANO:
What encouraged

00:28:06.230 --> 00:28:09.190
us to get back together?

00:28:09.190 --> 00:28:12.070
We always all did music.

00:28:12.070 --> 00:28:13.450
STEVEN DELOPOULOS:
Yoga, I think--

00:28:13.450 --> 00:28:14.200
THEODORE PAGANO: Yeah.

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:15.450
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: Helped
homelessness.

00:28:18.020 --> 00:28:20.200
When you walk into a Starbucks,
and you saw an

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:24.080
application for a job, then you
think maybe we should--

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:27.140
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS: Steven and
I are cousins, and so we've

00:28:27.140 --> 00:28:28.700
always played together.

00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:30.710
And that never ended.

00:28:30.710 --> 00:28:32.790
And Teddy was out in the
UK for a little bit.

00:28:32.790 --> 00:28:36.200
So I think what the inspiration
really was just we

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:36.830
had done it.

00:28:36.830 --> 00:28:38.250
We had had some success.

00:28:38.250 --> 00:28:41.070
But there were definitely things
that we wanted to do

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:43.790
that we never did then, because
we were too green and

00:28:43.790 --> 00:28:45.850
inexperienced.

00:28:45.850 --> 00:28:49.390
And so there is definitely
a fire under all

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:50.660
of us to do it again.

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:52.430
The question was, were we
actually going to do.

00:28:52.430 --> 00:28:56.700
And a few different situations
led us all to getting back

00:28:56.700 --> 00:28:58.130
together again.

00:28:58.130 --> 00:28:59.870
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: Teddy
was living in England--

00:28:59.870 --> 00:29:00.570
the drummer--

00:29:00.570 --> 00:29:02.040
and he came back.

00:29:02.040 --> 00:29:05.250
Me and Johnny were playing
music continuously.

00:29:05.250 --> 00:29:08.690
And I had written
all the songs.

00:29:08.690 --> 00:29:09.400
We have the songs.

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:10.510
We had most of them.

00:29:10.510 --> 00:29:15.620
We had a basement to start
rehearsing and a manager and a

00:29:15.620 --> 00:29:17.220
label that was interested
in signing us.

00:29:17.220 --> 00:29:18.280
And we just went for it.

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:20.140
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS: We sort of
went backwards, because we had

00:29:20.140 --> 00:29:23.150
some success and then came back
to just almost starting

00:29:23.150 --> 00:29:24.400
over again.

00:29:26.250 --> 00:29:28.930
Teddy thought that we might
score another deal, but Steven

00:29:28.930 --> 00:29:31.130
and I were just like,
we're old.

00:29:31.130 --> 00:29:33.730
Who's going to sign us again?

00:29:33.730 --> 00:29:36.090
We were picked up
by Sony Jive.

00:29:36.090 --> 00:29:38.630
It was almost like lightning
striking twice.

00:29:38.630 --> 00:29:41.026
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: Once we hit
19, it was like, it's over.

00:29:41.026 --> 00:29:41.740
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS:
It's over, yeah.

00:29:41.740 --> 00:29:42.630
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: It's all
downhill from here.

00:29:42.630 --> 00:29:43.530
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS:
Yeah, exactly.

00:29:43.530 --> 00:29:45.110
FEMALE SPEAKER: Now how did
you get meet with Brett?

00:29:45.110 --> 00:29:46.890
How did this all come about?

00:29:46.890 --> 00:29:53.740
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: Our manager
knew Brett's partner and we

00:29:53.740 --> 00:29:57.230
all met in LA at a really
cool diner.

00:29:57.230 --> 00:29:58.350
What was the diner called?

00:29:58.350 --> 00:29:59.190
BRETT LEONARD: Jerry's Deli.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:00.240
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: Jerry's
Deli, yeah.

00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:01.820
It's really, really
good actually.

00:30:01.820 --> 00:30:02.770
THEODORE PAGANO: It's just
a little cool diner.

00:30:02.770 --> 00:30:07.450
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: And we sat
down with Brett and just had a

00:30:07.450 --> 00:30:08.270
conversation.

00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:11.870
And we actually were all
a little starstruck.

00:30:11.870 --> 00:30:17.130
We knew who he was, and were
very excited to meet him, and

00:30:17.130 --> 00:30:20.710
dumbfounded why he was
talking to us.

00:30:20.710 --> 00:30:22.220
FEMALE SPEAKER: Brett, why were
you talking to you guys?

00:30:22.220 --> 00:30:24.980
BRETT LEONARD: I listened
to the album.

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:29.100
I didn't want to choose who I
was doing this first frag film

00:30:29.100 --> 00:30:33.530
with based upon anything but
just responding to the music

00:30:33.530 --> 00:30:35.720
and responding to who
the people are.

00:30:35.720 --> 00:30:37.850
Because that's one of the things
that just drives me

00:30:37.850 --> 00:30:42.780
crazy, the hierarchy of how
content happens it isn't a

00:30:42.780 --> 00:30:44.470
true meritocracy.

00:30:44.470 --> 00:30:47.120
And so I just want to
respond to that.

00:30:47.120 --> 00:30:48.530
I love the album.

00:30:48.530 --> 00:30:51.080
And I just saw, wow, I could
make a movie from this.

00:30:51.080 --> 00:30:54.520
And they're so authentic in the
fact, when I went and saw

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:57.870
them after we met and saw them
perform live the first time,

00:30:57.870 --> 00:31:00.130
that I was truly hooked.

00:31:00.130 --> 00:31:03.210
Because I wanted to do something
where you didn't

00:31:03.210 --> 00:31:05.880
have to, in a sense, fake
the music in any

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:07.250
way, shape or form.

00:31:07.250 --> 00:31:10.400
And there's not one moment of
fake music in this movie.

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:14.680
It's purely capturing them in
their live performance, which

00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:17.056
is truly wonderful.

00:31:17.056 --> 00:31:19.260
They're very virtuosic in
they're performance.

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:21.940
FEMALE SPEAKER: And it's very
unique to have completely live

00:31:21.940 --> 00:31:23.800
music in a film.

00:31:23.800 --> 00:31:26.120
Was that liberating
for you guys?

00:31:26.120 --> 00:31:28.070
Or was that difficult?

00:31:28.070 --> 00:31:30.860
Were you worried that there's
no post-production?

00:31:30.860 --> 00:31:31.660
THEODORE PAGANO: No.

00:31:31.660 --> 00:31:34.220
That's the type of
band that we are.

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:36.600
We don't use electronics.

00:31:36.600 --> 00:31:40.440
We're very much like
a '70s folk band.

00:31:40.440 --> 00:31:41.640
We get together to play.

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:43.240
We have chemistry
with each other.

00:31:43.240 --> 00:31:44.260
And that's our thing.

00:31:44.260 --> 00:31:45.180
So it's quite natural for us.

00:31:45.180 --> 00:31:47.140
FEMALE SPEAKER: So it was kind
of liberating for you guys.

00:31:47.140 --> 00:31:47.250
It was just all natural.

00:31:47.250 --> 00:31:47.740
THEODORE PAGANO: Yeah.

00:31:47.740 --> 00:31:49.230
We just did our thing.

00:31:49.230 --> 00:31:51.570
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS: It was
actually nice, because the

00:31:51.570 --> 00:31:56.250
record that Brett heard
was all recorded--

00:31:56.250 --> 00:31:58.360
Pro-tools was used as the
medium just because it's

00:31:58.360 --> 00:31:59.580
cheaper to capture it there.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:03.620
But the computer screen was
not allowed in the room.

00:32:03.620 --> 00:32:07.050
There was no auto-tuning
and no editing.

00:32:07.050 --> 00:32:07.681
FEMALE SPEAKER: Which is so
cool and completely unique

00:32:07.681 --> 00:32:07.920
these day, I feel like.

00:32:07.920 --> 00:32:08.300
JOHN PHILIPPIDIS: There
was no nudging.

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:09.090
Yeah.

00:32:09.090 --> 00:32:10.260
It was just live.

00:32:10.260 --> 00:32:14.100
And the fact that they were
going to capture it that way,

00:32:14.100 --> 00:32:15.930
that's all we know
how to do anyway.

00:32:15.930 --> 00:32:20.740
So post-production to us
is not really even a--

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:22.430
BRETT LEONARD: Burlap to
Cashmere for me, was a band

00:32:22.430 --> 00:32:26.000
that deserved to have
a movie made.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:28.950
And I just wanted that to be the
reason, because we're not

00:32:28.950 --> 00:32:31.120
spending millions of dollars
doing these.

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:33.080
We're spending hundreds of
thousands of dollars, but

00:32:33.080 --> 00:32:34.080
we're not spending millions
of dollars.

00:32:34.080 --> 00:32:36.930
So there's a liberating
aspect to that.

00:32:36.930 --> 00:32:39.260
And independent cinema used
to be about that.

00:32:39.260 --> 00:32:42.000
It used to be about doing
something truly authentic.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:43.600
As I mentioned John Cassavetes,

00:32:43.600 --> 00:32:45.060
he's one of my heroes.

00:32:45.060 --> 00:32:48.440
And if you go back and see the
things he talked about, about

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:52.280
what drove him to make the
cinema he did, that is me

00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:54.980
returning to those roots.

00:32:54.980 --> 00:32:56.995
Even though I hadn't done these
kinds of films before, I

00:32:56.995 --> 00:33:00.150
had done films that were much
more visual effect oriented

00:33:00.150 --> 00:33:00.800
and all that.

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:05.450
So really for me, it was a
liberating experience from

00:33:05.450 --> 00:33:07.170
doing a different
kind of cinema.

00:33:07.170 --> 00:33:09.940
And because they're so
authentic, and then they were

00:33:09.940 --> 00:33:13.000
able to play versions of
themselves very authentically,

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.540
it was again, this great
confluence of things.

00:33:16.540 --> 00:33:17.670
FEMALE SPEAKER: And a very
unique experienced for

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:19.170
everyone, I'm sure.

00:33:19.170 --> 00:33:21.120
Now, guys, when you first heard
about the frag film

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:22.820
concept, what was
your reaction?

00:33:22.820 --> 00:33:25.990
How did you feel that it would
assist musicians or the music

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:28.290
genre in general?

00:33:28.290 --> 00:33:30.145
THEODORE PAGANO: We struggled to
understand it at first and

00:33:30.145 --> 00:33:33.120
I think a lot of people do.

00:33:33.120 --> 00:33:38.730
The idea of it a manager said,
so we have this on Friday, and

00:33:38.730 --> 00:33:41.150
then there's this, and then, oh
we might be making a movie.

00:33:41.150 --> 00:33:42.510
We're like, what.

00:33:42.510 --> 00:33:43.760
STEVEN DELOPOULOS:
Pass the salt.

00:33:45.970 --> 00:33:48.770
THEODORE PAGANO: So he tried
to explain it as best as he

00:33:48.770 --> 00:33:51.600
could, but we didn't really
understand it until we met

00:33:51.600 --> 00:33:53.350
with Brett and he
explained it.

00:33:53.350 --> 00:33:55.465
BRETT LEONARD: That's one of the
reasons I just went ahead

00:33:55.465 --> 00:33:56.940
and made the film.

00:33:56.940 --> 00:34:00.240
Because I wanted to show, until
we have all the frags

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:02.410
out there and then we release
the film, now everyone's

00:34:02.410 --> 00:34:03.100
starting to get it.

00:34:03.100 --> 00:34:03.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's easier
to wrap your head around.

00:34:03.370 --> 00:34:06.640
BRETT LEONARD: People were
going, oh I see.

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:09.139
Oh, you're giving it
away for free.

00:34:09.139 --> 00:34:14.239
All of those ideas are counter
to the way in which Hollywood

00:34:14.239 --> 00:34:19.179
cinema distribution has worked
for forever that it's new.

00:34:19.179 --> 00:34:22.760
But that for me, is
why I get up.

00:34:22.760 --> 00:34:25.880
That's what drives me is to do
something new and different

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:29.610
that can empower both people
that watch films and also

00:34:29.610 --> 00:34:30.659
people that make them.

00:34:30.659 --> 00:34:32.409
FEMALE SPEAKER: My first
question when I started doing

00:34:32.409 --> 00:34:35.690
the research was, how does it
differ from a trailer or a

00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:37.170
teaser for a film?

00:34:37.170 --> 00:34:42.409
BRETT LEONARD: Essentially, it's
making the film be a lot

00:34:42.409 --> 00:34:44.330
of teasers, a lot of trailers.

00:34:44.330 --> 00:34:47.770
And you're seeing this
happen in bigger

00:34:47.770 --> 00:34:49.530
studio films, as well.

00:34:49.530 --> 00:34:53.000
You're seeing secondary material
being put out before

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.830
big films like Prometheus,
things that are put out as--

00:34:55.830 --> 00:34:57.430
FEMALE SPEAKER: People
want [? even more. ?]

00:34:57.430 --> 00:34:57.720
BRETT LEONARD: Yeah.

00:34:57.720 --> 00:34:58.630
They want [? even more. ?]

00:34:58.630 --> 00:35:01.810
And so this is a way of doing
it with more independent

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:06.610
cinema and giving away even more
so that if you like it,

00:35:06.610 --> 00:35:08.420
then it's authentic that
you want to buy it.

00:35:08.420 --> 00:35:10.710
It's not like, to see that
big movie I've got to

00:35:10.710 --> 00:35:13.850
spend $19.95 on iTunes.

00:35:13.850 --> 00:35:16.795
And I think that's not going to
be the way that independent

00:35:16.795 --> 00:35:18.760
cinema works in the future.

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:21.290
FEMALE SPEAKER: What is the
overall theme of this

00:35:21.290 --> 00:35:21.980
particular film?

00:35:21.980 --> 00:35:24.440
What is the message?

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:27.320
BRETT LEONARD: Well again, it
comes out of the music for me.

00:35:27.320 --> 00:35:32.400
I'm sure that the musicians
themselves would have a more

00:35:32.400 --> 00:35:35.430
deep answer in terms of where
the music comes from.

00:35:35.430 --> 00:35:39.730
But for me, it was about
this journey.

00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:41.860
And so we created a journey,
in a sense.

00:35:41.860 --> 00:35:44.710
But Steven could probably speak
to that better than me.

00:35:44.710 --> 00:35:45.860
STEVEN DELOPOULOS: Brett
had it right.

00:35:45.860 --> 00:35:48.880
I think when Brett wanted to do
the project first, it was

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:50.000
about The Other Country.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.350
It was about the other side.

00:35:52.350 --> 00:35:55.660
And I believe we had a
conversation about close

00:35:55.660 --> 00:35:57.670
family or friends who
had passed on, and

00:35:57.670 --> 00:36:00.420
that was our bond.

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:06.610
And I think the film really was
inspired and like, well,

00:36:06.610 --> 00:36:08.620
what happens to those people
that you love and that are so

00:36:08.620 --> 00:36:10.980
close to you and you lose them,
and they die, or they

00:36:10.980 --> 00:36:12.410
leave and this and that.

00:36:12.410 --> 00:36:18.730
And so The Other Country was
this antidote to that reality

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:21.980
that as human beings, we all
have to go through and face.

00:36:21.980 --> 00:36:26.370
And I think Brett was really,
really keen on making that the

00:36:26.370 --> 00:36:30.880
focal point in the film.

00:36:30.880 --> 00:36:37.120
When I wrote the music, the
lyrics were the focal point of

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:41.660
I see the other country, just
basically like, it's the

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:45.360
ultimate near death experience
record, hopefully.

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:47.610
And I think Brett got
that and wanted to

00:36:47.610 --> 00:36:48.980
capture it, and he did.

00:36:48.980 --> 00:36:52.080
BRETT LEONARD: And I think
because we made it a journey

00:36:52.080 --> 00:36:56.490
across this country, and we've
been in a lot of interesting

00:36:56.490 --> 00:36:58.280
foment in this country lately.

00:36:58.280 --> 00:37:02.130
There's a bit of for me, also a
political angle there that's

00:37:02.130 --> 00:37:03.980
expressed in purely
the visuals.

00:37:03.980 --> 00:37:05.740
It's not something that we
put in the narrative.

00:37:05.740 --> 00:37:08.130
It's purely expressed in
the cinematic language.

00:37:08.130 --> 00:37:09.030
FEMALE SPEAKER: What is it?

00:37:09.030 --> 00:37:14.170
BRETT LEONARD: Well, just that
there's more than one America.

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:16.470
And even moreso now than
ever we see that.

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:19.920
But if you go back and you watch
Lincoln, you'll see it's

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:22.100
been that way for
very long time.

00:37:22.100 --> 00:37:26.320
And so for me, all those themes
that were more mystical

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:33.900
in nature also reflect in the
overall geography and nature

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:34.320
of this country.

00:37:34.320 --> 00:37:36.240
And I've traveled across
the country.

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:38.380
I hitchhiked across the country
when I was a teenager.

00:37:38.380 --> 00:37:43.280
I love traveling America,
because it literally is like

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:47.220
traveling through multiple
countries.

00:37:47.220 --> 00:37:50.320
And people from outside of here
see that even moreso than

00:37:50.320 --> 00:37:52.020
people that come from here.

00:37:52.020 --> 00:37:54.660
And so I wanted to express that
but not in an overhanded

00:37:54.660 --> 00:37:59.550
way, just in a way that was
touched in inside the visual

00:37:59.550 --> 00:38:00.460
language of the film.

00:38:00.460 --> 00:38:01.720
FEMALE SPEAKER: I definitely
thought what you're saying

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:05.170
through some of the frags that
I watched on the website when

00:38:05.170 --> 00:38:06.450
you guys are playing
in the club.

00:38:06.450 --> 00:38:09.295
And it's a bunch of hillbillies
and at first they

00:38:09.295 --> 00:38:10.200
don't know what's going on.

00:38:10.200 --> 00:38:12.470
And you're like, oh great,
we've got to do this.

00:38:12.470 --> 00:38:14.160
And then they totally
get the vibe.

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:15.420
So it was really interesting.

00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:16.970
BRETT LEONARD: That frag
you're talking

00:38:16.970 --> 00:38:18.630
about is frag two.

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:21.540
Those are real people.

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:25.770
For me, again, the neo-realism
format of going in and just

00:38:25.770 --> 00:38:28.090
going into a bar literally
saying, we're going to buy

00:38:28.090 --> 00:38:29.090
drinks for everybody.

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:30.020
Come on down.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.570
Those are just real people
responding in a real way to

00:38:32.570 --> 00:38:33.990
hear music as they played it.

