00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:29.900
We want to utilize some of the
new technological things that

00:50:29.900 --> 00:50:34.400
allow interactivity that can
connect with additional

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:39.610
material, second screen
experiences.

00:50:39.610 --> 00:50:42.540
Obviously with different kinds
of music and different kinds

00:50:42.540 --> 00:50:44.350
of subject matter,
there's other

00:50:44.350 --> 00:50:46.140
opportunities that could come.

00:50:46.140 --> 00:50:49.680
This piece is a very organic
piece that comes directly from

00:50:49.680 --> 00:50:52.090
the organic nature of the
band and the music.

00:50:52.090 --> 00:50:55.940
As I said, they play
the music live.

00:50:55.940 --> 00:50:59.280
We didn't want to add on
interactivity on top of that

00:50:59.280 --> 00:51:01.540
in a way that was inappropriate
to the vibe of

00:51:01.540 --> 00:51:02.320
this particular piece.

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:04.610
So this really is the
kernel for which.

00:51:04.610 --> 00:51:07.280
But I'm very, very interested
in interactivity.

00:51:07.280 --> 00:51:10.260
My son, who's part of that and
Christopher [? Creaver ?],

00:51:10.260 --> 00:51:14.690
who's heading that up,
their passion is

00:51:14.690 --> 00:51:16.780
finding ways to interact.

00:51:16.780 --> 00:51:20.570
We're developing some projects
that are more science fiction

00:51:20.570 --> 00:51:24.490
based, things like that that
are going to have a genre

00:51:24.490 --> 00:51:27.810
component to them that allows
much more interesting

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:29.060
interactivity.

00:51:31.240 --> 00:51:32.150
FEMALE SPEAKER: Anybody else?

00:51:32.150 --> 00:51:33.420
BRETT LEONARD: And if there's
anyone at Google that wants to

00:51:33.420 --> 00:51:36.380
play with us, we're very
open to doing--

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:40.310
I love what Chris Milk did with
the Arcade Fire piece.

00:51:40.310 --> 00:51:43.090
That was truly an emotional
use of interactivity.

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:45.900
And so those are the kinds of
things that interest me.

00:51:45.900 --> 00:51:49.900
AUDIENCE: I just wanted to ask
you about the filming style

00:51:49.900 --> 00:51:51.900
that you used.

00:51:51.900 --> 00:51:54.400
In some places, it was like an
Instagram video and you used

00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:55.650
the saturated colors.

00:51:57.400 --> 00:51:59.900
Why did you choose to do that?

00:51:59.900 --> 00:52:02.540
BRETT LEONARD: Well, I
started doing HD--

00:52:02.540 --> 00:52:04.790
I was one of the first people
to ever use HD--

00:52:04.790 --> 00:52:07.010
years, and years,
and years ago.

00:52:07.010 --> 00:52:13.320
So are the ability to post
process images, which

00:52:13.320 --> 00:52:17.000
Instagram is a consumer
version of, is been

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:18.730
around for a while.

00:52:18.730 --> 00:52:21.630
And that's a style I've been
developing with a lot of my HD

00:52:21.630 --> 00:52:23.520
projects in different ways.

00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:25.140
This was very specific--

00:52:25.140 --> 00:52:28.070
using grain, using image
degradation, using those kinds

00:52:28.070 --> 00:52:29.320
of things as a style.

00:52:31.940 --> 00:52:35.430
We have a saying at [INAUDIBLE],
we'd push all the

00:52:35.430 --> 00:52:39.440
buttons just to try everything
that exists

00:52:39.440 --> 00:52:40.720
and see what works.

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:43.200
Because I think there can
be a celebration of

00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:45.440
HD as its own aesthetic.

00:52:45.440 --> 00:52:48.250
I love film, and film is
a tremendous aesthetic.

00:52:48.250 --> 00:52:49.835
But HD is really a
different medium.

00:52:49.835 --> 00:52:53.240
It's like oils and acrylics.

00:52:53.240 --> 00:52:56.140
From a creative standpoint, I
think it could be pushed even

00:52:56.140 --> 00:53:00.620
more in terms of doing things
that truly make it unique to

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:01.340
its own medium.

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:03.737
And so we're trying
to do that.

00:53:03.737 --> 00:53:05.685
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
using an iPhone?

00:53:05.685 --> 00:53:07.640
What are some of the
other cameras?

00:53:07.640 --> 00:53:14.580
BRETT LEONARD: 5D, 7D because
this was no permits, complete

00:53:14.580 --> 00:53:15.300
guerrilla filmmaking.

00:53:15.300 --> 00:53:19.430
We did a whole scene by they're

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:21.030
rehearsal basement in Brooklyn--

00:53:21.030 --> 00:53:22.910
in the street of Brooklyn--

00:53:22.910 --> 00:53:27.086
and suddenly there were all
these detectives around

00:53:27.086 --> 00:53:30.950
walking down the street going in
canvas because some murder

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:31.910
that took place.

00:53:31.910 --> 00:53:34.450
And we're shooting a movie in
the middle of that, and not

00:53:34.450 --> 00:53:35.630
one of them batted an eye.

00:53:35.630 --> 00:53:38.230
Because with the 5D and 7D, it
looks like you're shooting

00:53:38.230 --> 00:53:39.520
skills, or whatever.

00:53:39.520 --> 00:53:42.380
And so the freedom of that,
which is very again, much the

00:53:42.380 --> 00:53:45.880
Cassavetes style and the
neo-realism style, it just

00:53:45.880 --> 00:53:49.870
allows again, an authenticity
that you just can't get with a

00:53:49.870 --> 00:53:51.530
different kind of
filming style.

00:53:51.530 --> 00:53:53.140
There are new cameras
coming up.

00:53:53.140 --> 00:53:55.630
Now, I would shoot a whole
one of these with

00:53:55.630 --> 00:53:58.540
just the iPhone now.

00:53:58.540 --> 00:54:00.100
These are great cameras.

00:54:00.100 --> 00:54:03.590
Image acquisition is not the
issue at this point.

00:54:03.590 --> 00:54:05.590
AUDIENCE: Also because you
weren't capturing sound.

00:54:05.590 --> 00:54:06.100
BRETT LEONARD: We were
capturing sound.

00:54:06.100 --> 00:54:07.710
AUDIENCE: You were capturing
sound on the iPhone?

00:54:07.710 --> 00:54:08.610
BRETT LEONARD: No, not
on the iPhone.

00:54:08.610 --> 00:54:10.620
We had separate sound.

00:54:10.620 --> 00:54:11.730
We had separate sound,
defintely.

00:54:11.730 --> 00:54:14.770
But the zoom--

00:54:14.770 --> 00:54:19.780
as mobile and as lean as
possible to get the quality.

00:54:19.780 --> 00:54:21.420
Again, it goes back
to expertise.

00:54:21.420 --> 00:54:23.740
One of the things that we want
to share with people is with

00:54:23.740 --> 00:54:26.690
these very, very simple tools,
if you have a certain

00:54:26.690 --> 00:54:30.570
expertise, you can make things
that are just as high quality

00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:31.580
as Hollywood does.

00:54:31.580 --> 00:54:32.620
It's just about the expertise.

00:54:32.620 --> 00:54:34.590
So you have to add
that layer in.

00:54:34.590 --> 00:54:36.730
And that's one of things
PopFictionLife wants to do.

00:54:36.730 --> 00:54:39.180
That's part of the interactivity
with the

00:54:39.180 --> 00:54:41.340
community, because
there are tricks.

00:54:41.340 --> 00:54:46.300
There's a lot of tricks that
you learn over the years.

00:54:46.300 --> 00:54:50.540
I just I just love the freedom
that these kinds of cameras

00:54:50.540 --> 00:54:51.700
and technologies allow.

00:54:51.700 --> 00:54:54.450
And it really has to get back
to getting something

00:54:54.450 --> 00:54:56.700
authentic, getting something
new, getting something that

00:54:56.700 --> 00:55:00.850
you discover while you're
making a film.

